column1: #Text=Located in the province of Vicenza , Marostica ( Maròstega in Veneto dialect ) is famous all over the world for the human chess game it carries out every other year , with personages living in the city public square .
#Text=The heart of the Marostica is enclosed by its Medieval wall , with both an Upper and Lower castle , and the living chess game square being right at the centre of the town .
#Text=And the Scaligeri nobles from Verona were the key protagonists of Marostica ’s important and still visible past .
#Text=In addition to its very charming and very lively Medieval atmosphere , Marostica is also famous for the different varieties of cherries which are produced in the area .
#Text=Local cherries bear the PGI ( protected geographical indication ) mark and have long been celebrated in local markets , festivals and , of course , culinary tradition .
#Text=Marostica has a direct bus connection with Vicenza railway station .
#Text=Alternatively , a direct bus connection exists with Bassano railway station too .
#Text=More info is available on Trenitalia 's website .
#Text=Venezia Marco Polo ( VCE ) , 85km , lot of destinations throughout Europe - by train : bus to Venice station , then train to Vicenza or Bassano , then bus
#Text=Treviso ( TSF ) , 52km , low-cost airport with Ryanair and other carriers - by train : bus to Treviso station , then train to Vicenza , then bus
#Text=Marostica is 30km north-east of Vicenza , which can easily be reached through the A4 Milano-Venezia highway ( Vicenza Est and Vicenza Ovest exits ) .
#Text=FTV directly connects Marostica to Bassano ( 15min ) and Vicenza ( 45min ) .
#Text=Discovering the town on foot is very easy .
#Text=The historic centre is not very big , so you can easily go around in the narrow streets .
#Text=And you can also walk all around its Medieval walls from the Lower up to the Upper Castle , but this is a bit more demanding .
